author: @rssaiganesh
text: 1. Version Control - Git  - commit codes to the codebase and keep track of changes. Also, keep a master version of code  - Work on different features on separate branches - organization and collaboration tool.  -GIT  2. Database - SQL  - Object Related Mapping - ORM SQL in python - NoSQL DBs  - just do a simple hello world application in some of these databases and see what you like best    3. Command-Line and Terminal  - Search files and move files etc. Important for Web Dev and Servers.  - We need to know way around to operate around the command line in the machine. - for windows user, try Linux terminal  4.  Unit Testing. Continuous Integration & Continuous Delivery Unit Testing Libraries.   -  as Central Repo to check code.   - refer to Jenkins.io   /   travis-ci.org   5.  Learn Multiple Programming Languages.  - diff languages are just syntaxes. - knowing how to solve problems is what takes time.  - solve problems in multiple languages.  I just wrote this summary. Do let me know if any corrections. And thank you so much Corey for the brilliant video.

author: @christianhorauf9958
text: A good video. BUT there is missing one and maybe the most imporant aspect. I think I fullfill about 3-4 of the presented aspects. And I feel pain, everytime somebody violates best practices that come along with these aspects or programming itself. But a skill that is missing this list and I also feel a lack of is softskills. What does it help you, if you know how to do things right but you can not present them in a way that others buy in. Unittesting for example. I am practicing this skill for more then three years now and I think I know now how to use it. But still I get accused of testing too much. And to be honest I am not sure if those accusations are true or not. But if I would have better softskills and moved more teammates into the promised lands of TDD I would have a much easier life. So maybe you should make a Video about Softskills themselfs and how to lern them.

author: @Cyberfoxxy
text: I was at an interview applying for a project with some serious dough. I passed all the questions but the interviewer flipped on one question.  Client: "What database should be used for a Unity3D iOS MMO Game?"  Me: "It doesn't really matter"  Client: "I see, thank you for your time."  Me: "Ok.. so to elaborate on my answer. It's doesn't matter because most database solutions out there all do pretty much the same thing which is RDMS. Everything is agnostic. And for performance they all perform slightly different in some operations. But whether we  should use MSSQL, MySQL or MongoDB is simply an irrelevant question."  Client: "So you really think it doesn't matter?" Client: "I'm sorry but you are not what we're looking for." Client: "And just as a note. We are always for solving different problems, that's why we have 5 CORE languages in the world."  Me: "Choose between them? Are you kidding, you reach a point as programmer where the programming language doesn't matter anymore" Me: "I can program in 15 different languages, I don't even know what "CORE languages" are. And while we're talking; Unity3D you don't "choose" the better language cause there is only C#, and even further the database is not even gonna be running on the client side so anything is free of choice and the API will remain identical on the client side." Me: "We can optimize performance once we get performance issues, but stuff like real-time positioning should NEVER be pulled from the database in real-time, but rather it should stored in the servers memory because NO DATABASE recommends polling at 50ms intervals per client! So if you have 1000 users that's 20'000 lookups PER SECOND, any database system flat out crash!"  *Message not delivered, you are not on users contact list.*
